Dr. Carstairs<p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 42<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/7/02 7:26:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=314.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: NASA</span><hr size=1> I disagree with the previous 2 comments here.  <br>
<br>
While I feel strongly that NASA needs to restructure and reorganize, as well as redefine its missions and goals, I do not feel that it is a waste of time or money.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, I do not think that blocking &quot;commercial space exploitation&quot; is a bad thing.  I am in favor of colonizing space, and getting necessary materials from space,but not &quot;exploting&quot; it. If space were rapidly opened up to the journeys of corporations, the world would see a great deal of problems.  First, companies would spend so much money trying to get into space that they would go backrupt.  Second, space is not a territory to be claimed, in my opinion, but that's what businesses would do.  I can just see Phillip Morris landing on the moon and then staking claim to it, charging royalties when people look at it.  They would of course be outdone by Time Warner or Microsoft when a mission made it to Mars and claimed property rights on it.  The commercialization of space would only bring about bad things right now.  Involving private sector in space research and exploration would be wonderful, but they would need to be supervised and looked after. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=stilgar>Stilgar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/7/02 2:44:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=314.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Nasa / commercial endeavors</span><hr size=1> I'd like to respond to a few of your comments:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> <br>
First, companies would spend so much money trying to get into space that they would go backrupt.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I disagree.  I think that any sound, well managed business can get into space with simply a moderate expenditure of money, a good business plan, and a dollop of passion.  <br>
You might as well claim &quot;businesses will spend so much money building factories that they will go bankrupt.&quot; Space is an environment full of possibilities.  Smart, well managed groups can exploit those possibilities to make a profit and, in the process, convince the public that space is available and exciting.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Space is not a territory to be claimed, in my opinion, but that's what businesses would do. ... The commercialization of space would only bring about bad things right now. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
There is more than enough space to go around.  if you look up, the only thing you can see is space.  you see that little speck that is jupiter?  You know how large that is.  Space is the only territory it makes sense to claim.<br>
If Philip Morris were to land on the moon and stake a claim, I would not dispute them.  Indeed, I would laud them for the first private extraterrestrial landing.<br>
<br>
I agree with you that the private sector should be supervised and regulated, but only to the extent to avoid frivolous claims.  <br>
If Phillip Morris landed and claimed the WHOLE moon, or an area the size of California even, I would not recognize it, and I dont think anyone else would either.  If, however, they demonstrated that they needed 2 square miles for a mining operation, I think they should be allowed to get it.   People desiring that same land should have to buy/rent it from them.  I have no problems with that.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> While I feel strongly that NASA needs to restructure and reorganize, as well as redefine its missions and goals, I do not feel that it is a waste of time or money.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I agree that NASA needs to restructure and reorganize.  Until it does so, its a waste of time and money.<br>
<br>
Nasa, like many government organizations, is run on a &quot;cost plus&quot; system.  The profit for their contractors is determined as a percentage of their costs.  If Nasa wants a sensor package, it makes sense for the contractor (since its a government contractor, they usually just stick with one) to run costs up.  If your profit is (say) 10% of cost, then it makes no sense to buy a bolt from the hardware store for .15$.   It makes a lot more sense to helically machine a 1lb lump of titanium for a cost of 130$ and put 5 engineers at 100$/hour on a task force with the goal of justifying the new titanium bolt with FEA analysis and static testing.  In the end you have a cost of about 5000$ per bolt, which earns you a profit of 500$/bolt.  As opposed to the .015$/bolt you'd get otherwise.  <br>
<br>
Once the government changes the way they do business, I'll agree that it is not a waste of money to give it to NASA.  I think the private sector does things a lot cheaper, faster, and more efficiently than NASA.  XCOR built a flying rocket prototype (the EZ-rocket)for half a million.  Thats less than NASA's breakfast pastry budget.<br>
<br>
Stilgar out. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/udrcarstairs.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DrCarstairs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Utterly Mad Scientist</span><br>  Posts: 73<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/8/02 12:16:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=314.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.imgstudio.com/original/032820021216063.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nasa / commercial endeavors</span><hr size=1> First, can one of the moderators resize this thread so it fits the page? It’s annoying to have to constantly pan left and right juts to read a post. I finally started copying the post and pasting them into Word to avoid a headache.<br>
<br>
Next, definitions:<br>
<br>
Exploitation (N) - an act or instance of exploiting &lt;exploitation of natural resources&gt; &lt;exploitation of immigrant laborers&gt; &lt;clever exploitation of the system&gt;<br>
<br>
Exploit (TV) - 1 : to make productive use of : UTILIZE &lt;exploiting your talents&gt; &lt;exploit your opponent's weakness&gt;<br>
2 : to make use of meanly or unjustly for one's own advantage &lt;exploiting migrant farm workers&gt;<br>
Definitions courtesy of <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://http//www.m-w.com">Merriam-Webster OnLine</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Now, I was using exploitation as the productive utilization of resources. If you think that is bad, tough. Someone will eventually exploit space. Personally, I want it to be individuals and companies that can be held liable should they do anything wicked (for want of a better word). A government agency, protected by sovereign immunity – no, very bad idea. <br>
<br>
In a perfect world, NASA would be helping companies get into space instead of obstructing them. NASA makes money by exploiting space, and as a government agency it should not.  <br>
<br>
And so what if Philip Morris lands on the moon and claims a part of it. Property rights are a cornerstone of a free society. And at least they would be doing something, as opposed to the current situation.<br>
